WEBVTT
X-TIMESTAMP-MAP=LOCAL:00:00:00.000,MPEGTS:144533

1
00:00:02.035 --> 00:00:05.438
So far, our queries
have been done in a single forward pass.

2
00:00:05.939 --> 00:00:08.808
Given the query, call the right tool
with the right parameters

3
00:00:08.808 --> 00:00:10.510
and get back the response.

4
00:00:10.510 --> 00:00:12.545
But this is still quite limiting.

5
00:00:12.545 --> 00:00:16.683
What if the user asks a complex question
consisting of multiple steps,

6
00:00:16.683 --> 00:00:19.419
or a vague question
that needs clarification?

7
00:00:19.419 --> 00:00:22.155
In this lesson,
you will learn how to define a complete

8
00:00:22.155 --> 00:00:25.892
agent reasoning loop. Instead of tool
calling it in a single shot setting,

9
00:00:26.092 --> 00:00:29.462
an agent is able to reason over tools
and multiple steps.

10
00:00:30.263 --> 00:00:34.000
You will use the function calling
agent implementation, which is an agent

11
00:00:34.000 --> 00:00:37.470
that natively integrates with the function
calling capabilities of LLMs.

12
00:00:38.204 --> 00:00:38.772
All right.

13
00:00:38.772 --> 00:00:41.908
Let's have some fun. To get started,

14
00:00:42.108 --> 00:00:45.111
we'll set up our OpenAI key.

15
00:00:46.413 --> 00:00:48.281
And then we'll set up and import asyncio.

16
00:00:48.281 --> 00:00:48.681
17
00:00:50,483 --&gt; 00:00:50,950
For now

17
00:00:50.950 --> 00:00:54.120
we use the same Meta GPT paper as the previous
two lessons.

18
00:00:54.721 --> 00:00:57.290
In the next lesson
we'll expand to the multi-doc setting.

19
00:00:57.290 --> 00:01:00.326
And we will also set up
the auto retrieval factor search tool

20
00:01:00.360 --> 00:01:02.896
and the summarization tool
from the last lesson.

21
00:01:02.896 --> 00:01:04.064
To make this more concise,

22
00:01:04.064 --> 00:01:06.933
we've packaged this
into a single line of code

23
00:01:06.933 --> 00:01:09.702
that you can just import
from the utils module.

24
00:01:09.702 --> 00:01:12.505
We now set up our function calling agent.

25
00:01:12.505 --> 00:01:13.840
As with the previous notebooks,

26
00:01:13.840 --> 00:01:16.142
we use Jupyter 3.5 turbo

27
00:01:16.142 --> 00:01:19.712
as our LLM.
We will then define our agent.

28
00:01:20.947 --> 00:01:22.115
In LlamaIndex,

29
00:01:22.115 --> 00:01:25.051
an agent consists of two main components:

30
00:01:25.051 --> 00:01:28.021
an agent worker,
as well as an agent runner.

31
00:01:28.488 --> 00:01:30.890
Think of an agent worker that's responsble

32
00:01:30.890 --> 00:01:35.528
for executing the next step
of a given agent and an agent runner, or a

33
00:01:35.628 --> 00:01:39.399
the overall task dispatcher,
which is responsible for creating a task

34
00:01:39.732 --> 00:01:43.069
orchestrating runs of agent worker
on top of a given task,

35
00:01:43.470 --> 00:01:46.473
and being able to return back
the final response to the user.

36
00:01:49.442 --> 00:01:51.177
So we import both function calling

37
00:01:51.177 --> 00:01:54.414
agent worker from LlamaIndex
and also the agent runner.

38
00:01:55.515 --> 00:01:59.252
And for the function calling agent worker,
we pass in the two set of tools,

39
00:01:59.786 --> 00:02:02.789
the vector tool,
as well as the summary tool.

40
00:02:03.957 --> 00:02:07.327
We also pass in the LLM
and set verbose equal to true

41
00:02:07.327 --> 00:02:10.330
to look at the intermediate outputs.

42
00:02:11.364 --> 00:02:14.534
Think about the function calling
agent workers primary responsibility

43
00:02:14.934 --> 00:02:18.271
as given the existing conversation
history, memory

44
00:02:18.271 --> 00:02:21.241
and any passed state
along with the current user input.

45
00:02:21.875 --> 00:02:24.878
Use function
calling to decide the next quote or call.

46
00:02:25.378 --> 00:02:28.781
Call that tool and decide
whether or not to return a final response.

47
00:02:29.382 --> 00:02:32.785
The overall agent interface
is behind the agent runner, and that's

48
00:02:32.785 --> 00:02:35.788
what we're going to use to query
the agent.

49
00:02:37.223 --> 00:02:39.225
Well, first ask this question.

50
00:02:39.225 --> 00:02:42.195
"Tell me about the agent roles
in Meta GPT

51
00:02:42.195 --> 00:02:43.997
and then how they
communicate with each other."

52
00:02:53.173 --> 00:02:56.142
So let's
trace through the outputs of this agent.

53
00:02:56.142 --> 00:03:01.142
We see that the agent is able to break
down this overall question into steps.

54
00:03:01.314 --> 00:03:04.717
So the first part is asking
about agent roles and Meta GPT.

55
00:03:05.652 --> 00:03:08.655
And it calls the summary tool
to answer this question.

56
00:03:08.988 --> 00:03:12.158
Now a quick note is that the summary tool
isn't necessarily the most precise.

57
00:03:12.425 --> 00:03:16.396
You could argue that the vector tool
will actually give you back a more concise

58
00:03:16.396 --> 00:03:20.033
set of context that better represents
this relevant pieces of text

59
00:03:20.033 --> 00:03:20.934
that you're looking for.

60
00:03:20.934 --> 00:03:23.937
However, a summary tool
is still a reasonable tool for the job.

61
00:03:24.070 --> 00:03:29.070
And of course, more powerful models like
Four Turbo or Cloud three, Sonnet or Opus

62
00:03:29.509 --> 00:03:33.046
might be able to pick the more precise
vector tool to help answer this question.

63
00:03:33.446 --> 00:03:37.083
In any case, we see that we're able
to get back the output, the agent roles

64
00:03:37.083 --> 00:03:40.086
in Meta GPT include product Manager, architect,

65
00:03:40.286 --> 00:03:43.289
project manager, QA, engineer, etc.

66
00:03:43.456 --> 00:03:47.527
And then it uses this to perform
chain of thought to then trigger

67
00:03:47.527 --> 00:03:52.232
the next question, which is communication
between agent roles and Meta GPT.

68
00:03:54.000 --> 00:03:56.536
We see we're able to get back an answer
about that too.

69
00:03:56.536 --> 00:03:58.972
You know, communication
between agent roles and Meta GPT

70
00:03:58.972 --> 00:04:01.741
is structured and efficient,
and we're able to combine this

71
00:04:01.741 --> 00:04:04.711
entire conversation history
to generate a final response.

72
00:04:06.546 --> 00:04:07.580
Communication.

73
00:04:07.580 --> 00:04:10.583
And Meta GPT include the agent roles include these.

74
00:04:10.650 --> 00:04:14.120
They collaborate in a sequential manner
to follow standard operating procedures.

75
00:04:14.821 --> 00:04:17.156
And they use a shared message

76
00:04:17.156 --> 00:04:20.159
and subscription method mechanism.

77
00:04:20.393 --> 00:04:22.462
When you run a multi-step query like this,

78
00:04:22.462 --> 00:04:25.465
you want to make sure that you're
actually able to trace the sources.

79
00:04:25.832 --> 00:04:28.368
And so luckily,
similar to the previous lessons,

80
00:04:28.368 --> 00:04:30.570
we're able to look at response
that source notes

81
00:04:30.570 --> 00:04:33.573
take a look
at the content of these notes.

82
00:04:33.840 --> 00:04:38.011
So this allows you to for instance,
inspect the content of the first source

83
00:04:38.011 --> 00:04:41.014
note that's retrieved,
which is just the first page of the paper.

84
00:04:41.581 --> 00:04:44.083
Calling agent query allows you to query

85
00:04:44.083 --> 00:04:47.086
the agent in a one off manner,
but does not preserve state.

86
00:04:47.353 --> 00:04:50.123
So now let's try maintaining
conversation history over time.

87
00:04:51.391 --> 00:04:51.958
The agent

88
00:04:51.958 --> 00:04:55.128
is able to maintain chats
in a conversational memory buffer.

89
00:04:55.862 --> 00:05:00.099
The memory module can be customized,
but by default it's a flat list of items

90
00:05:00.099 --> 00:05:03.403
that's a rolling buffer depending on the
size of the context window of the LLM.

91
00:05:04.437 --> 00:05:07.440
Therefore,
when the agent decides to use a tool

92
00:05:07.674 --> 00:05:11.744
and not only uses a current chat,
but also the previous conversation history

93
00:05:11.744 --> 00:05:14.747
to take the next step or perform
the next action.

94
00:05:16.049 --> 00:05:18.951
So instead of query, we'll do agent dot chat.

95
00:05:18.951 --> 00:05:21.754
The first thing we'll ask
is "tell me about the evaluation

96
00:05:21.754 --> 00:05:24.757
data sets used."

97
00:05:27.393 --> 00:05:28.561
Here we see that

98
00:05:28.561 --> 00:05:31.998
it uses the summary tool to ask
what are the evaluation data sets.

99
00:05:31.998 --> 00:05:34.200
Use and Meta GPT.

100
00:05:34.200 --> 00:05:36.135
And we see the eval data sets used

101
00:05:36.135 --> 00:05:39.439
include human eval MVP and software dev.

102
00:05:43.976 --> 00:05:45.511
You'll see an example of this

103
00:05:45.511 --> 00:05:49.082
ability to maintain conversation history
because we'll ask a follow up question.

104
00:05:49.549 --> 00:05:52.485
Tell me the results over one of the above
data sets.

105
00:05:52.485 --> 00:05:55.922
Obviously, to know what the above data
sets are, you have to have that stored

106
00:05:55.922 --> 00:05:58.891
in the conversation history somewhere.

107
00:06:00.693 --> 00:06:01.294
So let's run

108
00:06:01.294 --> 00:06:05.365
this and it's able to translate this query
plus conversation

109
00:06:05.365 --> 00:06:08.468
history
into a query on the vector tool actually.

110
00:06:08.735 --> 00:06:11.738
And it asks results over the human eval
data set

111
00:06:11.771 --> 00:06:14.540
which is one of the eval
data sets are used.

112
00:06:14.540 --> 00:06:17.543
And it's able to give you back
final answer.

113
00:06:17.710 --> 00:06:21.280
So we just provided a nice high level
interface for interacting with an agent.

114
00:06:22.315 --> 00:06:24.584
And this next section
will show you capabilities

115
00:06:24.584 --> 00:06:28.221
that let you step through and control
the agent in a much more granular fashion.

116
00:06:28.488 --> 00:06:31.290
This allows you to not only create
a higher level research assistant

117
00:06:31.290 --> 00:06:34.293
over your RAG pipelines,
but also debug and control it.

118
00:06:34.761 --> 00:06:38.431
Some of the benefits include greater
debug ability and to the execution

119
00:06:38.431 --> 00:06:42.402
of each step, as well as steerability
by allowing you to inject user feedback.

120
00:06:42.802 --> 00:06:46.806
Having this low level agent interface
is powerful for two main reasons.

121
00:06:47.407 --> 00:06:49.308
The first is debug ability.

122
00:06:49.308 --> 00:06:52.111
If you're a developer building an agent,
you might want to have greater

123
00:06:52.111 --> 00:06:56.549
transparency and visibility into what's
actually going on under the hood.

124
00:06:56.816 --> 00:06:59.952
Especially, say, if your agent isn't
working the first time around.

125
00:07:00.453 --> 00:07:04.791
Then you can actually go in and trace
through the execution of the agent,see

126
00:07:04.791 --> 00:07:05.725
where it's failing,

127
00:07:05.725 --> 00:07:09.228
and actually try out different
inputs to see if that actually modifies

128
00:07:09.228 --> 00:07:12.198
the agent execution
into a correct response.

129
00:07:12.198 --> 00:07:16.402
Another reason why this could be useful
is actually enable richer UXs,

130
00:07:16.602 --> 00:07:20.139
where you're building a product experience
around this core agent capability.

131
00:07:20.706 --> 00:07:24.043
For instance, let's say you want to listen
to human feedback

132
00:07:24.310 --> 00:07:26.279
in the middle of agent execution,

133
00:07:26.279 --> 00:07:29.916
as opposed to only after the agent
execution is complete for a given task.

134
00:07:30.550 --> 00:07:33.553
Then, you can imagine
creating some sort of async queue,

135
00:07:33.753 --> 00:07:34.754
where you're able to listen

136
00:07:34.754 --> 00:07:39.025
to inputs from humans
throughout the middle of agent execution.

137
00:07:39.392 --> 00:07:43.863
And if human input actually comes
in, you can actually interrupt and modify

138
00:07:43.863 --> 00:07:47.700
the execution of an agent
as it's going on through a larger

139
00:07:47.700 --> 00:07:51.070
task, as opposed to having to wait
until the agent task is complete.

140
00:07:51.671 --> 00:07:54.073
So we'll start by defining our agent again

141
00:07:54.073 --> 00:07:57.443
through the function calling agent worker,
as well as the agent runner setup.

142
00:07:57.677 --> 00:08:00.446
And then we start using the low level API.

143
00:08:00.446 --> 00:08:03.449
We'll first create a task object
from the user query.

144
00:08:03.850 --> 00:08:06.953
And then we'll start running through steps
for even interjecting our own.

145
00:08:07.286 --> 00:08:10.389
Now let's try executing
a single step of this task.

146
00:08:10.957 --> 00:08:12.558
So let's create a task for this agent.

147
00:08:12.558 --> 00:08:15.761
And we'll use the same question we used
in the very first part of this lesson.

148
00:08:16.229 --> 00:08:18.364
"Tell me about the agent roles in Meta GPT

149
00:08:18.364 --> 00:08:20.366
and then how they communicate
with each other."

150
00:08:20.366 --> 00:08:23.369
This will return a task object
which contains the input

151
00:08:23.669 --> 00:08:26.672
as well as additional state
in the task object.

152
00:08:26.906 --> 00:08:29.909
And now let's try executing
a single step of this task.

153
00:08:30.676 --> 00:08:33.646
We'll call agent dot run step task dot

154
00:08:33.646 --> 00:08:35.615
Task ID.

155
00:08:35.615 --> 00:08:39.018
And the agent will execute a step of that
task through the task ID

156
00:08:39.252 --> 00:08:40.553
and give you back a step output.

157
00:08:46.225 --> 00:08:46.626
We'll see

158
00:08:46.626 --> 00:08:49.695
that it calls the summary tool
with the input agent

159
00:08:49.695 --> 00:08:52.698
roles and Meta GPT, which is a very first part
of this question.

160
00:08:53.366 --> 00:08:56.369
And then it stops there.

161
00:08:58.304 --> 00:08:59.705
When we inspect the logs

162
00:08:59.705 --> 00:09:04.043
and the output of the agent, we see
that the first part was actually executed.

163
00:09:05.144 --> 00:09:08.447
So we call agent that completed
steps on the task I.D..

164
00:09:09.081 --> 00:09:12.084
And we're able to look at NUM
completed for the task.

165
00:09:14.587 --> 00:09:17.290
We see that one step has been completed.

166
00:09:17.290 --> 00:09:20.293
And this is a current output so far.

167
00:09:20.993 --> 00:09:24.297
We can also take a look
at any upcoming steps for the agent.

168
00:09:24.664 --> 00:09:27.667
And we can do this through agent
to get upcoming steps.

169
00:09:29.902 --> 00:09:33.072
Again we pass the task
that task ID and to the agent,

170
00:09:33.506 --> 00:09:36.609
and we're able to print out the number
of upcoming steps for the task.

171
00:09:37.376 --> 00:09:40.780
We see that it's also
one and we're able to look at a task step

172
00:09:40.780 --> 00:09:44.216
object with a task
ID as well as an existing input.

173
00:09:44.550 --> 00:09:48.020
This input is currently "none",
because the way the agent works

174
00:09:48.020 --> 00:09:52.291
is actually just auto generates, action
from the conversation history

175
00:09:52.558 --> 00:09:55.461
and doesn't need to generate
an additional external input.

176
00:09:55.461 --> 00:09:57.330
The nice thing about this
debugging interface

177
00:09:57.330 --> 00:10:00.333
is that if you wanted to pause execution
now, you can.

178
00:10:00.666 --> 00:10:03.703
You can take the intermediate results
without completing the agent flow.

179
00:10:04.704 --> 00:10:05.905
But let's keep going,

180
00:10:05.905 --> 00:10:10.076
and let's run the next two steps
and actually try and drafting user input.

181
00:10:11.677 --> 00:10:14.347
So let's actually ask:
"what about how agents

182
00:10:14.347 --> 00:10:17.350
share information as user input."

183
00:10:17.483 --> 00:10:21.687
This was not part of the original
task query, but by injecting this,

184
00:10:21.687 --> 00:10:24.957
this can actually modify agent execution
to give you back the result

185
00:10:24.957 --> 00:10:27.960
that you want.

186
00:10:28.427 --> 00:10:31.430
We'll see that
we added the user message to memory,

187
00:10:31.530 --> 00:10:34.100
and that the next call here
is how agents actually

188
00:10:34.100 --> 00:10:37.103
share information in Meta GPT.

189
00:10:38.838 --> 00:10:39.538
And we see here

190
00:10:39.538 --> 00:10:42.508
that is able to give back the response.

191
00:10:42.942 --> 00:10:45.211
The overall task is roughly complete.

192
00:10:45.211 --> 00:10:48.214
And we just need to run one final step
to synthesize the answer

193
00:10:48.247 --> 00:10:50.816
and to double check
that this output is the last step,

194
00:10:50.816 --> 00:10:53.052
we just need to
do step output.is_last.

195
00:10:57.123 --> 00:10:58.324
So we see we're able to get

196
00:10:58.324 --> 00:11:01.627
back the answer about how agents
and Meta GPT share information.

197
00:11:02.161 --> 00:11:04.797
And this is indeed the last step.

198
00:11:04.797 --> 00:11:07.867
To translate this into an agent response

199
00:11:07.867 --> 00:11:11.303
similar to what we've seen in
some of the previous notebook cells,

200
00:11:11.737 --> 00:11:14.306
then all you have to do is call
response equals

201
00:11:14.306 --> 00:11:17.276
agent dot finalist response.

202
00:11:18.577 --> 00:11:21.580
And we're able to get back
the final answer.

203
00:11:25.384 --> 00:11:26.986
So that's it for lesson three.

204
00:11:26.986 --> 00:11:28.888
You've learned both
about the high level interface

205
00:11:28.888 --> 00:11:31.857
for an agent as well as a low level
debugging interface.

206
00:11:32.058 --> 00:11:34.727
And in the next lesson
we'll show you how to build an agent

207
00:11:34.727 --> 00:11:35.761
over multiple documents.

